metadata.name: The Happiness Of All Mankind #15
Quantum Places Lost in Time #183
metadata.description:
A frozen scene from a lost dimension
An alternative of where we once were, or where we will be 
Caught in the moment and set in place
Between all states
Static pixels on a digital canvas

The path to this collection has created many alternatives lost in time themselves. It began as a study of points of light, with geometric objects in the background. The background objects developed a life of their own and then birds, and ships, made out of bezier shapes became the focal points. Then everything got lost in clouds before the collection as it stands now emerged. Aside from the published traits, many of the artifacts created on the way are still generated. For example, star fields, birds, sonars and gas bubbles. These are sometimes visible, but when they appear, it is simply by some chaotic chance.

This collection has been coded with P5js and WebGL. Half of all primary sales proceeds, and secondary royalties, are assigned to the Processing Foundation.

Press s to download a 2880 x 3840 jpeg

This work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial 4.0 International License.

metadata.name: Overgrowth #70
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of random growth focused on three interconnected elements. The first is a randomly moving brush, the second is one is an alternating overlay of white and black circles along bezier points between brush movements, and the final one being a continually decreasing brush size.

The overall result gives a complex scribble art effect. 

Created with p5.js

metadata.name: STRUCTURES #304
metadata.description:
STRUCTURES

What color do things look when you're happy?

First of all I want to dedicate this collection to all the people who paint their emotions with color, who through a chromatic range, are capable of feeling a universe of sensations most of the time inexplicable.....

 I am fascinated by how generative art creates a perfect symbiosis between art and technology, allowing through a set of algorithmic rules to give rise to compositions where shapes and colors coexist in balance, harmonized with each other that give rise to new creations.

This collection is designed to be self-contained and limited, recreating the view from different angles and phases of the day that can lead to disparate interpretations of a piece.

My work as a visual artist explores elements such as randomness and chance of linear formations and geometric gradients that broaden the spectrum to increasingly new concepts that I definitely want to explore.

I continually wonder what the geometric patterns that will emerge from my sensibility will be like and will give rise to new collections like this one, which is why I continue to investigate techniques and shapes while having fun.

"A painting is not the image of an experience, but it is the experience." Mark Rothk

metadata.name: Morphing Convictions #112
metadata.description:
Everyday we move on by relying on our convictions. Their immutability often helps us take decisions or take shelter but can sometimes clash with the unknown, the different and the new. They can then crack, crumble and mutate. To change your convictions means changing the kind of person you want to be. It means changing your self-identity. And that is not just hard, it is scary. And beautiful.

Morphing Convictions is a piece that exists through two kind of outputs : Posters and Scenes. Posters are focusing on the contemplation of details and movements of a morphing conviction while the Scenes are interactive little worlds where you can explore a conviction in it's environment.

Please open in live mode to enjoy a much better experience.

Controls :

Posters & Scenes
‚Ä¢ Click anywhere to enable audio.
‚Ä¢ Press M to toggle mute.
‚Ä¢ Press F to toggle the fullscreen mode.
‚Ä¢ Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

Scenes only
‚Ä¢ Drag and scroll to rotate and zoom.
‚Ä¢ Click on objects, some might react.

metadata.name: The dice is cast #23
metadata.description:
When I started studying the code and learning the "random" functions in early July 2022, it made me think of randomness when throwing dice. It is random, but with these restrictions (3 six-sided dice = 216 possibilities). 

With this mindset and theme, I began to create this first attempt at generative art. 

In my usual work, I take everyday objects, materials, etc. and play with them. For this series, I inserted blocks of polystyrene to give it substance. 

All the graphic elements, colours and random arrangements were created using P5.js. The photos of polystyrene and the dices are integrated.

Press ENTER to download as a jpg image. 

@Yomu Oyashi July 2022

The NFT licence 2.0

metadata.name: k3rnel #50
metadata.description:
Self-organizing future-jazz geometry for like-minded pixel based neighbourhoods. 


********
Glossary
********

'Self-organization' ‚Üí the process by which individuals organize their communal behaviour to create global order by interactions amongst themselves rather than through external intervention or instruction.

'Future-jazz-geometry' ‚Üí propulsive syncopated visual rhythms, polyphonic ensemble playing, varying degrees of improvisation, and often deliberate distortions of pitch and timbre.

'Like-minded' ‚Üí sharing the same opinions, ideas, or interests. 

'Pixel' ‚Üí the smallest addressable element in an all points addressable display device; so it is the smallest controllable element of a picture represented on the screen.

'Neighbourhood' ‚Üí a spatial unit, in which face-to-face social interactions occur.

Touch to listen, go fullscreen

metadata.name: citylines #150
metadata.description: For this project, I decided to learn how to code up isometric buildings using just lines, custome shapes, and fills. Pretty fun actually. In the process, some interesting distributions of buildings kept popping up - like buildings on the outer edges only for example. So I made them explicit features (City Splits). The variations you can expect are colors, city splits (trio is my favorite!), building pattern type (i love lines :)), max building height, and # of pyramids. I hope you get some amazing outputs! Enjoy :)

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
‚ÄúIn Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art‚Äù 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke‚Äôs MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it‚Äôs a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

‚ÄúOur goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke‚Äôs 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the R√ºtgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.‚Äù 

Each frame, a single ‚Äúpixel‚Äù is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely ‚Äî it‚Äôs an ‚Äúinfinite animation.‚Äù

metadata.name: CRAYONS #195
metadata.description:
Sometimes we like the feeling of being citizens of the places we visit. Our senses adapt to capture in detail the signs of the environment. It is then when we begin to breathe the color that surrounds us and places us in that unique setting.

This is how this inspired collection is born and grows, the colors that enchant us as children on a sheet of paper and now serve to paint every place we visit.

The 6 color palettes of this collection aim to transport us to all those places.

Paris: Its pastel tones strolling along the Trocadero on the banks of the Seine.

Berlin: How to tell the story with color in the graffiti of the East Side Gallery and the wall.

Mexico: Its flavor is in the rainbow of its embroideries, alebrijes and altars.

Kenya: Sunrises and sunsets that impregnate the retina with the tones of the savannah.

Costa Rica: Pure life, pure green, from gentle to intense Monte Lluvioso.

Colombia: Seas of flowers flood the streets with colors and aromas celebrating the Feria De Las Flores

High-resolution png downloads are available by pressing number keys 1 (3000px), 2 (6000px), or 3 (9000px).
